The VIN is HA4-2319911. This is a very clean example and runs great with no leaks. Suspension feels tight, engine is smooth and strong with smooth shifting through all gears and the timing belt was changed at 90,000km. The exterior is 3.5-4 out of 5 overall with a very clean bed and just a few small rust spots.  All of the lights work, clear headlights, strong parking brake and everything works as intended. All three tailgates fold down or come off to create a flatbed for easy loading. This is the perfect utility truck and is ideal for hauling loads of up to 750 pounds. Actys run on 87 gas, get about 45 mpg and cruise well between 55 and 65 mph. The truck comes with standard silver 12" steel rims and hubcaps but powder coated color rims are available for an additional cost. Please visit our website to view our full inventory and all available add ons. We have been doing this for years and have brought this truck in legally from Japan. We encourage buyers in the area to swing by the shop to inspect vehicles in person if possible. We also are willing to do FaceTime with customers who are too far to come in person, who would like to see the vehicle before purchasing. We have flexible hours, just contact us to set up a time.  TITLE AND REGISTRATION Our right hand drive collection has been imported under the EPA 25 year exemption. Most states will allow these vehicles to be registered and driven as regular vehicles, but California will not without completing CARB compliance testing first. You can still purchase this vehicle for OHV or private land use without having to complete any CARB testing. If you're a California buyer, please let us know if you have any additional questions on this matter. For buyers outside the state of California, these are street legal and can be driven as a regular vehicle on most roads. We will provide all documentation needed to register and title the vehicle. The documents which will be provided include the Export Certificate/Japanese title as well as the English translation, NHTSA HS-7 Form, EPA Form 3520-1 and CBP Form 7501. We will also send you an invoice and upon full payment, a Bill of Sale. If you have any questions regarding the paperwork provided, please don't hesitate to contact us directly.

Contact Rob 864-505-5621 for any questions, please visit my website for more pictures.  The ninth generation Carry (and third generation Every) appeared in September 1991.The 657 cc F6A engine remained from the previous generation, but an all-new bodywork was much smoother, originally with slim, small rectangular headlights. The chassis was largely unchanged for the truck (albeit with a somewhat longer wheelbase), but the vans had a considerably longer wheelbase and an engine mounted midships, just ahead of the rear axle. Chassis codes changed accordingly, and were now different for the Carry and the Every. The trucks are DC/DD51T and the vans are DE/DF51V ("DD" and "DF" for four-wheel drive versions). Two different front treatments were available, one with small rectangular aerodynamic headlights and one with large, round units (used on lower-spec models).  The ninth-generation Carry received a very gentle facelift in September 1993, which meant that the front drum brakes were switched to discs on all models. Two months later the Carry Van line switched to the Every nameplate and the division between trucks and vans was made clearer yet. Another light change occurred in July 1995, when the front turn signals were changed from clear to amber and the bolt pattern was changed from 114.3 to 100 mm. This generation continued to be built until 1999. Most export markets continued to receive the previous generation Carry, with bigger engines and most commonly with van bodywork. The older Super Carry is generally more rugged than the DE/DF51, which was fitted with a coil sprung De Dion rear axle not as suitable for carrying heavy loads. In those rather few foreign markets where the ninth-generation Carry was available, it was sold as the SK306 and with a version of the 657 cc engine used in the Japanese Domestic Market. In late 1997, the retro-styled Suzuki Every C arrived.
